Data Inspection, Cleaning, and Feature Engineering
1. Data Inspection
The first step in any data analysis process is to inspect the dataset thoroughly. In this phase, we focused on understanding the structure of the dataset and identifying any potential issues that could affect the analysis. The key tasks during this phase included:
  •	Checking Dataset Shape: We started by reviewing the number of rows (records) and columns (variables) in the dataset to ensure it was as expected.
  •	Reviewing Column Names: The column names were examined to ensure they matched the expected structure and to identify any inconsistencies.
  •	Identifying Missing Values: We checked for missing data across all columns to understand which fields had incomplete records.
  •	Checking for Duplicates: Duplicate rows were identified and removed to avoid redundant analysis.
  •	Inspecting Data Types: We checked the data types of each column (e.g., numerical, categorical, datetime) to ensure they were correctly formatted for analysis.

2. Data Cleaning
Data cleaning is an essential step to ensure that the dataset is ready for in-depth analysis. In this phase, we focused on handling missing values, data type conversion, and duplicates:
  •	Handling Missing Values: We detected columns with missing values, particularly the Gender column, and imputed missing values using the mode (most frequent value) for categorical fields.
  •	Date Formatting: The Purchase Date column was converted to datetime format to enable time-based analysis such as month, quarter, and year extractions.
  •	Removing Duplicates: Any duplicate rows in the dataset were removed to prevent redundant analysis and ensure clean data for modelling.
  •	Validating Data Integrity: After cleaning, we validated the dataset again to ensure there were no missing values or errors in the critical columns such as Revenue, Customer ID, and Order Status.

3. Feature Engineering
Feature engineering transforms raw data into meaningful features that can be used for analysis and modelling. In this phase, we created several new features to enhance the dataset and provide deeper insights:
  •	Month, Quarter, and Year Extraction: We extracted Month, Quarter, and Year from the Purchase Date column to allow for time-based analysis and to understand trends over time.
  •	Revenue Calculation: A new Revenue column was created by multiplying the Quantity and Unit Price (or using the Total Price if it was already present) to ensure accurate revenue reporting.
  •	Customer Segmentation:
  o	Total Spend by Customer: We aggregated the data by Customer ID to calculate the total spend by each customer, helping identify high-value customers.
  o	Purchase Frequency by Customer: We calculated the purchase frequency for each customer to understand how often they made purchases.
  •	Age Grouping: We created age groups (e.g., 18-25, 26-35, etc.) to segment customers into meaningful categories, which can help identify target demographics.
  By performing these data inspection, cleaning, and feature engineering steps, we ensured that the dataset was ready for in-depth exploratory data analysis (EDA) and further advanced analysis.
