Summary of Cleaning & Feature Engineering Steps:
  •	Inspection: Checked dataset dimensions, missing values, duplicates, and data types.
  •	Cleaning: Handled missing data, removed duplicates, and formatted dates correctly.
  •	Feature Engineering: Created new time-based features (Month, Quarter, Year) and calculated Revenue and customer-related metrics (total spend, purchase frequency).

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
In the EDA phase, we aimed to understand the dataset's structure, identify patterns, and uncover relationships between variables. Key steps included:
1.	Dataset Overview: Checked the shape, columns, and data types to ensure the dataset was structured correctly.
2.	Missing Data: Identified and handled missing values to prevent any distortions in analysis.
3.	Duplicates: Checked for and removed any duplicate rows to ensure data accuracy.
4.	Summary Statistics: Reviewed summary statistics (mean, median, etc.) of numerical columns to identify trends and outliers.
5.	Correlation Analysis: Assessed correlations between numerical variables to identify relationships.
6.	Categorical Data Exploration: Explored the distribution of categorical features (e.g., Age Group, Gender, Payment Method).
7.	Revenue Breakdown:
  o	Analysed revenue by month to spot seasonal trends.
  o	Explored revenue by age group and payment method to identify key drivers of revenue.
8.	Outlier Detection: Identified and assessed outliers to ensure data quality.
Key Insights:
  •	Discovered seasonal revenue patterns and variations.
  •	Identified significant age groups and payment methods driving revenue.
  •	Cleaned data for further analysis.

Behavioural Analysis
In the Behavioural Analysis phase, we aimed to understand customer behaviour by segmenting customers, analysing their purchase patterns, and identifying trends. The key aspects considered include:
1.	Customer Segmentation:
  o	We segmented customers into Top 20% (high spenders) and Bottom 20% (low spenders) based on their total spend.
  o	Further segmentation identified high spenders with low frequency (top spenders but low purchase frequency) and frequent buyers with low spend (frequent buyers but lower spend).

2.	Repeat vs New Customers:
  o	We identified repeat customers (those with more than one purchase) and calculated their percentage in the dataset.
  o	We also determined the average purchase frequency of repeat customers, helping understand customer loyalty and retention.

3.	Trend Analysis:
  o	Monthly Revenue Growth: We calculated the month-over-month growth in revenue to identify peak periods and seasonal patterns.
  o	Peak Month: We identified the month with the highest revenue, highlighting the period with the most customer activity.
  o	Seasonal Spikes: We analysed months with significant growth (e.g., greater than 10%) to spot seasonal surges in customer behaviour.

4.	Additional Analysis:
  o	We explored revenue by quarter and age group for each year to identify which age groups and quarters generated the most revenue.
  o	We also analysed which age group generated the most revenue quarter-wise for each year, identifying high-value segments across different time periods.

Logic Behind the Analysis:
  •	Customer Segmentation helped in targeting high-value customers for retention strategies and identifying low-frequency high-spenders for potential upselling.
  •	Repeat vs New Customers provided insights into customer loyalty and helped gauge the effectiveness of marketing strategies.
  •	Trend Analysis and Seasonal Spikes helped identify seasonal trends, informing inventory management, marketing campaigns, and sales strategies

